    # [Scene: Mariselle Boardwalk | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch13_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low, steady murmur of the crowd; gulls distant; a soft percussion rhythm underlining conversation]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Mid-tempo, restrained piano motif]
    "You feel the boardwalk under your boots the way you feel the bones in your chest—solid, salt-etched, carrying weight. The crowd around you leans forward like a tide listening for a tide mark. Sora stands to"
    "your left, fingers curled almost possessively around a roll of flyers; Lina is to your right, eyes narrowed into a practiced assessment. Behind you, Maya's posture is a living anchor—short, direct, her raincoat shoulders squared against"
    "the wind."
    "You inhale. The air tastes of brine and used coffee; fog lifts in thin bands revealing the gray horizon. You remember Dr. Noor's last look—complex, braced—and you hold it up as a quiet reason to aim for something other than spectacle."
    show ari_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_navarro "I won't make this a theater."
    "You set the tone softly, measured."
    show sora_watanabe at right:
        zoom 0.7

    sora_watanabe "Don't let them drown us in procedure. They need to feel urgency."
    show lina_moreau at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_moreau "Urgency without structure is chaos. We need commitments."
    "You step forward on the wooden planks. Microphones thrust like thin stalks toward you; phones tilt up to capture the tilt of your face. Your Moleskine rests in your hand like ballast."
    "You speak, and your voice carries—not performative, but deliberate."

    ari_navarro "We don't have to choose only engineers or only activists. We can bind our decisions together—residents, scientists, and municipal officials—rotating leadership so power doesn't calcify. Legally binding oversight. Phased pilots. Community veto on relocations."
    "A rustle—not a cheer, not a hiss, but the sound of people recalibrating. Sora's jaw tightens; Lina's brows lift in a split-second you track like a barometric change."

    sora_watanabe "A council of committees won't stop a storm. How do we keep it from stalling when minutes matter?"

    ari_navarro "By designing action into the bylaws. Quick-response tiers, emergency triggers tied to science, and clear responsibility chains. We build structure that doesn't suffocate the people's voice."
    "Lina's voice is soft, an attempt to find fault without making enemies."

    lina_moreau "Rotating leadership is...ambitious. How will funding flow? How will we prevent capture by louder factions?"

    ari_navarro "Tie funding to phased criteria. Living shoreline pilots first—data checkpoints before next tranche. Community veto on relocations; municipal escrow accounts for maintenance—transparency built in."
    "Dr. Noor steps forward, the air around them carrying a faint smell of damp notebooks and ozone. Their hands are steady as they unfurl a printed model—corrected, annotated."
    hide ari_navarro
    show dr_noor_patel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_noor_patel "We ran layered-model scenarios. Single-solution strategies reduce some near-term risk but increase failure probability when variables compound. Combined, phased natural defenses plus targeted infrastructure reduce peak risk and buy time. It's not poetic; it's statistically better."
    "The murmurs shift. You hear the undercurrent of calculation—trust, doubt, an appraisal of contingency."
    "Sora's eyes meet yours—storm-dark, impatient—but something in the tilt of Dr. Noor's shoulders snaps a tiny hinge in Sora's posture."

    sora_watanabe "If the models hold—if the pilots scale—I'll support community oversight. But I want clauses: no secret deals, no backdoors."
    hide sora_watanabe
    show ari_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_navarro "Neither do I. Open ledgers, public meetings, rotating seats with term limits."

    menu:
        "Use the boardwalk microphone to invite a volunteer from the crowd.":
            "You call for a volunteer. Hands go up—old fishermen, a schoolteacher, a teenager with paint-stained fingers—voices that remind the crowd this plan is rooted in faces. The air lightens slightly with the proof of people willing to sign on."
        "Hand the microphone to Sora to issue a plain, urgent summary.":
            "You hand it to Sora. They compress the plan into a punchy, urgent phrase that ignites energy: 'A system that answers us. Not one that replaces us.' The crowd responds with a ripple of approval, but you sense the risk of momentum outpacing mechanisms."

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    "You listen to the small, charged exchanges. Negotiation is not just words; it's the slow choreography of demonstrating who will be there when the rain comes. Your chest tightens—not panic, but purpose assembling itself like a toolkit."
    # [Scene: Tidewatch Institute Greenhouse | Early Evening]
    hide lina_moreau
    hide dr_noor_patel
    hide ari_navarro

    scene bg ch13_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Dripping condensation, low clink of pens; evening insects rising in pattern]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A restrained string underscore; steady heartbeat rhythm]
    "You arrive with a small stack of drafts. The greenhouse smells of loam and salt—warm and alive, an odd domesticity amid crisis. Lina crosses her arms and walks the path between pots; Sora sits on the bench, knees splayed, flyers folded into neat stacks."
    "Maya Cruz appears with a binder of local histories and community petitions, placing it on the table like an offering."
    show maya_cruz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_cruz "If we're doing this, don't forget how the harbor used to be used—boat slips and old festivals. People need dignity, not just coordinates on a map."
    "You draft clauses with your hands aching from the day's momentum—paragraphs about rotating seats, a public ledger for funding, a phased pilot schedule, emergency triggers calibrated to Dr. Noor's updated models."
    show ari_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_navarro "Bylaw: emergency response tiers—Tier One: community-led living shoreline repairs. Tier Two: municipal deployment of temporary barriers. Tier Three: coordinated relocations initiated only after consensus thresholds."
    "Lina Moreau reads, finger tracing the clauses, her expression shifting from dialectic to consideration."
    show lina_moreau at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_moreau "We include municipal escrow. And a clause for third-party audits—annual, public. No single funder can unilaterally withdraw without council approval."

    ari_navarro "Agreed. And a community veto for relocations—exact language to be determined with legal counsel."
    "Dr. Noor leans over the table, tapping a line on a printout."
    hide maya_cruz
    show dr_noor_patel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_noor_patel "Add a clause: data checkpoints tied to funding release. If the pilot fails statistically at checkpoint two, we pause, assess, and adapt—no blind continuation."
    hide ari_navarro
    show sora_watanabe at right:
        zoom 0.7

    sora_watanabe "It feels like building a boat out of found crates—but if the seams hold, the boat moves people. I want to believe that."
    "You look at the rooftop through the greenhouse glass; the Tidewatch lights glow a steady amber. Your fitness-watch buzzes faintly against your wrist—barometer steady. Your hands ache from the late drafting sessions, paper cuts and salt-skin raw, but they move with practiced efficiency."

    menu:
        "Pause to call Dr. Noor's attention to a clause about community training.":
            "You suggest mandatory community-led training modules so residents can maintain living shorelines. Dr. Noor nods, noting reduced long-term failure rates. The clause is added; the sense of practical care grows."
        "Suggest a public trial in the Reclaimed Wetland Garden before municipal approval.":
            "You propose the wetland garden as a living lab. Maya lights up and volunteers surface immediately. The idea gives the bylaw a hands-on face—data and culture together."

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    "Conversation stretches and folds—lines are softened, countered, insisted upon. The dialogue is not clean; it is human: hesitant clauses, interjections that stop mid-sentence, laughter over a ridiculous legal turn of phrase, a barked correction, a rueful concession."

    lina_moreau "If this is truly binding, I will need written guarantees from the Development Authority and fiscal frameworks approved by the council."
    hide lina_moreau
    show maya_cruz at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_cruz "And I want grassroots representation—actual seats held by people who live here, not just people appointed for optics."

    sora_watanabe "No tokenism. Real power or nothing."
    "You push a pen across the table, signatures ready but not yet placed. The seal of compromise is the slowest kind of intimacy—the kind that forms between people who survive negotiation after negotiation."
    # [Scene: Reclaimed Wetland Garden | Morning Dusk]
    hide dr_noor_patel
    hide sora_watanabe
    hide maya_cruz

    scene bg ch13_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Quiet conversation, the distant hum of a desal pump, children's laughter echoing like a fragile bell]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle, optimistic piano motif; the tempo rises subtly]
    "A small delegation—residents, two municipal lawyers, Dr. Noor, Sora, Lina, and Maya—walk the garden with you. Tired faces, but aligned in the same direction. You point out where pilot cells could be dug, where access paths are necessary to maintain dignity and ritual for those who will relocate."
    show ari_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_navarro "We anchor culture—permits for community festivals in preserved pockets, boat slip allocations for local fishers, relocation assistance that includes cultural mapping."
    show lina_moreau at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_moreau "If we can guarantee cultural continuity as part of the legal framework, I will push for conditional municipal support."
    "Sora Watanabe watches you, then looks at Lina, then back to you—an orbit of trust forming, wobbling, steadying."
    show sora_watanabe at center:
        zoom 0.7

    sora_watanabe "This council better not become an excuse for bureaucratic delay."

    ari_navarro "Then we write timelines into the bylaws. Sunset clauses for reviews. Accountability measures."
    "You feel the energy rise—not a frantic peak, but a gathering momentum. Plans turn from ideas to documents to commitments. Community leaders step forward one by one—an elderly fisher, a teacher, a youth activist—placing names on"
    "a provisional roster. Each signature is a small, decisive vote in favor of a civic instrument that might hold."
    # [Scene: Municipal Offices | Night]
    hide ari_navarro
    hide lina_moreau
    hide sora_watanabe

    scene bg ch13_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft tap of keyboards; an occasional cough; the HVAC hum]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, sustained chord, forward-moving]
    "You read aloud the final lines you helped craft: rotating seats, emergency tiers tied to data, phased funding, community veto on relocations, public escrow accounts, third-party audits, cultural continuity clauses. Legal phrases that sound like care."
    show lina_moreau at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_moreau "This is not what I expected from a crowd-sourced proposal. It's…rigorous. It may be workable."
    show sora_watanabe at right:
        zoom 0.7

    sora_watanabe "Workable doesn't mean safe. But it means we are choosing to try in a way that preserves people."
    "You feel your shoulders lower just a fraction. The arousal has been steady—the workaday pressure of negotiation rather than adrenaline—and it has found a kind of forward momentum you can live with."
    show dr_noor_patel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_noor_patel "You did not concede principle for comfort. You built a process that can learn."
    "Your fitness-watch vibrates once—barometer steady, heart-rate within a determined range. Your palms sting from ink; the drafts are stacked, ready for official submission but not yet stamped."
    "You close your eyes for a beat and think of the town as a living ledger of people, not numbers, and of the crater grief that taught you to distrust single answers. This third way is"
    "precarious—like building a boat out of reclaimed crates—but when you imagine it afloat with people rowing, the image steadies you."
    "A quieter breath than a victory. Not an ending, but a deliberate, held promise."
    "You stand at the municipal lobby, papers in hand, surrounded by the faces who will carry this forward. Outside, the sea is a slow, gray promise. Inside, the amber light of Tidewatch lingers at the edges of your mind."
    "You let the thought sit—this is not a triumph; it is a beginning that chooses procedure as a form of care."
    "You raise your gaze to the faces around you. The council draft waits for signatures and schedules; negotiations at dawn will determine the first funding tranche and the exact language of emergency triggers."
    hide lina_moreau
    hide sora_watanabe
    hide dr_noor_patel

    scene bg ch13_453e40_5 at full_bg
